The paper uses information theory to establish lower bounds on the volume and surface area of geometric bodies, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with convex bodies and polyconvex sets, which are topics commonly studied in the cs.MG (Metric Geometry) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-categories. The paper also uses entropy bounds for log-concave random variables, which is a topic studied in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Finally, the paper investigates a new notion of Fisher information, which is a topic studied in the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
